      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a fascinating process involving the browning of food, like that lovely crust on your bread, and it's a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars when heat is applied. Think of it like a complex, delicious alchemy happening at the surface of your dough, which is what gives it that wonderful, complex flavor. You'll see this reaction happen when the temperature gets high enough, usually above 285°F (140°C), but the exact temperature depends on the specific ingredients and how quickly the heat is applied. If you keep the heat too low, the bread will just steam, and you won't get that glorious, crispy, brown exterior.",
