      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Controlling the process is a delicate balancing act, much like trying to herd a particularly skittish group of hungry little brown-and-yellow-spotted goblins! You can't just *force* the reaction to go slower without affecting the final product, but you can definitely manage the *rate* and the *intensity*.\n\nThe most direct way is indeed controlling the oven heat, but you can also manage the *surface* temperature. If you want a longer, more gradual browning without scorching, you might consider a two-stage bake. Start at a slightly lower temperature to allow the internal structure to set and the sugars to begin reacting gently, and then, perhaps, introduce a quick blast of higher heat right at the end for that final, deep color. This gives you more control than just blasting it from the start.",
